Dollar General Corporation DG | \(\) 111.48\$ In Line | Target Price/Base Case: \(\) 118.00\(from\) \ \(120.00\) Earnings Report
Company Statistics52-Week Range$66.43 - $125.42Base Case$118.00Upside/Downside5.6%Market Capitalization (M)$24,472Price/Earnings18.8Forward P/E18.3EV / EBITDA7.19Dividend Yield2.1%Short Interest3.7%
1 Year Price History

DG took a noteworthy step forward in its goal to stabilize share and reclaim \(6 - 7\%\) EBIT margin in 2Q. \(1.5\%\) traffic, a \(2.8\%\) comp, and 15bps of EBIT margin expansion to \(5.5\%\) are encouraging given the squishy low income consumer backdrop and inflationary cost pressure that DG and peers must navigate. We are bumping up our EPS to \(\) 6.10\(in C25, and\) \ \(6.35\) in C26 respectively reflecting the 2Q beat/solid back to school trends. We estimate that trade in may have benefited comps by 50- 100bps in the quarter, after backing out inflation impact of around 50- 75bps and a potential 50- 100bps from new stores/remodels. Multichannel initiatives like DoorDash and now the Uber Eats rollout are encouraging. Our Base Case of \(\) 118\(applies 18.5x recovering C26 EPS suggesting that there is more to like than not. That said, 2H25 isn't a slam dunk with the likely high single digit reduction in SNAP a potential 50- 100bp headwind to comp, our RSLI decelerating slightly into year end, and more challenging 2H25 compares. The test to unit elasticity will be profound as the impact of a 15pct pt plus step up in universal tariff rates is just being felt in earnest now. Key for DG's multiple will be finding a way to either sustain a \(3\% +\) comp steadily, or offset underlying wage/maintenance/ investment spend so that costs grow \(2 - 3\%\) or less on a same store basis. We see comps likely settling in at around \(2.5\%\) with some nice evidence of trade in from traffic and new store/renovation lifts. Competition is also likely to intensify given Amazon's push into same day fresh delivery and Walmart+ growth - we now peg at 18mn+ Households - see our survey here. We find KR appealing for value investors as it is better positioned than its 12.5x P/E multiple would suggest, in our view, while SFM offers solid unit growth and share gain prospects at a 23.5x C26 P/E as well.

What we liked: Positive traffic. Stabilizing share. Multichannel mojo. Gross margin expansion. Media business growth. Inventory. \(1.5\%\) traffic shows DG is driving frequency, with rising spend across all income demographics in the quarter. We believe trade in is a key part of the growth, reflecting improved in store experience and execution. DG also appears to be playing offense on price gaps, with a sub \(1\%\) rise in AUR vs. the \(2\% +\) rise of grocery CPI broadly to help sustain momentum. The \(2.8\%\) comp is slightly below the \(3\% +\) grocery industry growth in 3Q as per Census Bureau, but did improve from \(2.4\%\) in 1Q. DG's DoorDash partnership hits \(17k\) stores with \(60\% +\) YoY growth, while it is already offering Uber Eats in 4k stores with solid incrementality thus far. Over time we could see online penetration reaching \(3 - 5\%\) of sales Gross margin up 130bps doubled our expectation reflecting better shrink and damage performance which should remain as tailwinds into year end (albeit to a lesser extent). DG Media posted strong growth once more from a relatively nascent base, and we believe it should contribute 50- 100bps to EBIT margin, over time, even if half or more is reinvested, in our view. Inventory down \(7.4\%\) YoY per store helps efficiency/avoid shrink.
What to watch: Decelerating RSLI. SNAP. Competition. Cost inflation. Incentive comp. Reinvestment needs? Our Retail Sales

Lead Indicator moderates from \(4\%\) US Retail sales growth for the industry toward \(3\%\) into year end. Slowing payroll growth is a key culprit which suggests that DG's comps are likely to moderate somewhat even before factoring in tougher 2 year stacks. SNAP could pose a 50- 100bp headwind to comps as well, in isolation, in our view as our Strategy team projects a \(\) 5- 10bn\(reduction in annual SNAP payouts with initial signs likely by October, but building into late'26. Moves to lower tax are key offsets more in 1Q26; however, including Child Tax Credit, Social Security reduction and no tax to overtime/tips. Competition isn't letting up as Aldi continues its rapid growth pace, along with Amazon's Same Day Fresh push at 1k cities aiming for \(2k+\) by year end, and Walmart+ rising adoption. The good news is that for DG it has \(80\%\) of the U.S. within range of its store base, enabling 1 hour or less delivery as a standard via 3P carriers (for a cost). Incentive comp now projected at a \(\) 200\mathrm{mn}\$ headwind in C26 vs \(\) 180- 200\mathrm{m}\$ prior. DG is not immune to industrywide \(3\% +\) inflation for wages, plus rising utility/maintenance repair costs. While in store performance has been improving, risk remains for additional headcount investment needs over time, in our view.

Bottom Line: DG's turnaround is showing solid progress in 2Q reflected in the positive traffic, near \(3\%\) comp, and better than expected gross margin expansion. Building on the topline momentum to hit a steady \(3\% +\) comp, or finding a way to slow SG&A growth per store toward \(2\%\) would be key for enabling the unlock of 6- \(7\%\) EBIT margin long term goals. We aren't quite there, with a view that the choppy consumer backdrop and competitive set are likely to require more reinvestment in the core business for now. With KR trading sub \(13x\) our C26 EPS we like that stock as a deep value play in Food Retail that should be able to pass through food inflation while improving share/traffic thanks to the ESI offering. SFM at 23.5x offers an attractive entry point for growth investors with high single digit store growth and low to mid single digit comps sustainable, in our view.

Comps come in a traffic and discretionary driven +4%-+5% in '26-'28. Freight/transport conditions favourable, shrink/mix inflect enabling EBIT margin to surge toward 6%. 18-22x is a just a modest to in line S&P P/E discount as trust is regained, but still granted given the quick-than-anticipated turnaround.Turnaround persists, but labour reinvestment and mix/promo constrain margin recovery. DG comps 2.5% with modest gross margin expansion from mix/shrink that is offset by SG&A re-investment in wages/hours/training/tech which keeps EBIT margin below 5%. Store opening cadence holds at around 550-600 as mgmt. takes action to right the ship and cyclical headwinds moderate while initiatives gain traction.Hitting the reset button. Comps falter growing 1% or less as the low-income consumer is competed away by Walmart, Amazon, Dollar Tree and Aldi. DG invests in lower prices, while mix headwinds linger into '26. Gross margin falls 20-30bps, but wage inflation crunches SGA. SGA de-levers 20-40bps. EBIT margins free fall 60-80bps to 3.9%, ouch.
Source:Company Data,FactSet, Evercore ISI Research

Will DG be able to sustain positive traffic? Yes, around \(1\%\) . We believe DG fills a critical need for the lower income consumer. That said, a sustained traffic turn of \(2 - 3\%\) + would likely require further investment. The company's convenient store locations for rural America (within 5 miles of \(75 - 80\%\) of the U.S. population), small box, and value offering are long term share winners - with supply chain and store execution improving. With initiatives of DG Fresh, healthcare, and Back to Basics DG should grow traffic \(1\% +\)

What's the right EBIT margin for a mostly food and consumables (80% of mix) retailer? Aprox. \(5\%\) for the next 2- 3 years, and approaching \(5.5\%\) by 2028/2029. Previous hopes for pre- pandemic \(8\% +\) appear optimistic, with \(6 - 7\%\) DG Goal over 2- 3 years bullish, but not impossible. Rollout of an enhanced/higher margin assortment yields mix benefits via DG Fresh, NCI and services. Unlocking a meaningful boost from higher margin services/discretionary (50bps) and DG Media (100bps) with shrink (80bps) and damages (40bps) helping fund reinvestment.

Can DG return to a double digit EPS algorithm? Yes, but likely not until '28 or '29. We have EPS up \(3\%\) in '25, and then up \(4 - 9\%\) in '26- '27. Layering in incentive comp (i.e. was a \(\) 0.50\(headwind now a\) \ \(0.70\) for '25). Buybacks return slowly by '26, yet comps only return to \(2.5\%\) (ish) growth. \(+3\%\) comps, plus mix/shrink normalization likely needed for double digit EPS growth. Productivity levers are key to offset wage/hours but likely '26+.

1. A cyclical recovery drives discretionary mix higher providing a natural gross profit margin rate driver. 
2. A 80bp remaining shrink hit (as of 1Q25) since COVID reverses over 1-2-years. 
3. A 40bp damages hit since COVID reverses over 1-2 years. 
4. DG Fresh initiative drives traffic and boosts margins over a 3-4 year rollout span. 
5. Fast Track (Rolltainer) drives productivity as does Save to Serve initiative.

1. Grocery competition intensifies and continued share loss ensues 
2. Further wage rate and hour investment likely needed 
3. Entitlement spending cut crimps comps. 
4. Tariffs could clip profits by a low to mid single digit percentage.
